Astera Labs Scaling AI with PCIe, Ethernet, and UALink Retimers

Good morning everyone. My name is Anshul Sharma and I am here with my colleague and co-presenter Chris Blackburn representing Astera Labs. Our session covers an overall company portfolio update alongside our vision for AI Infrastructure 2.0 and a special section on retimers being implemented in modular server architectures.

Our mission at Astera Labs is simple yet profound: to unleash the full potential of AI through purpose-built rack-scale connectivity solutions. We are not building general-purpose networking gear that happens to work with AI. We are building products from the ground up that are intelligent and holistic to serve AI applications.

Intelligent connectivity starts with our connectivity ICs, boards, and modules. We ship signal conditioners including retimers and gearboxes, IO chiplets that go inside XPUs, controllers for different protocols, and AI fabric devices that address growing back-end bottlenecks for AI scale-up clustering. We offer these as ICs and boards so ecosystem partners can reach market faster, plus smart cable modules where our signal conditioning goes inside active electrical cables for within-rack and rack-to-rack links.

What makes the stack intelligent is our software-defined architecture and Cosmos—connected system management and optimization software for monitoring, fleet diagnostics, and fleet-wide management. Cosmos includes embedded software our customers and partners can extend, plus management interfaces and APIs to orchestrate racks in the AI infrastructure era.

We are rooted in open standards: PCI Express for within-rack and server connectivity, CXL for memory expansion, Ethernet for traditional scale-out, UALink for high-bandwidth low-latency scale-up fabric, and NVLink Fusion where Astera Labs participates. We have more than seven R&D centers worldwide, with recent openings in Vietnam, Singapore, Irvine, and Seattle.

We are focused on rack-scale vision because the industry is shifting from AI Infrastructure 1.0 to 2.0. In 1.0 the server was the unit of compute—you might put four or eight GPUs in a server and scale out with traditional networking when models were smaller. In 2.0 the entire rack must operate as a high-performance computing system: clusters of 32, 64, 128, or hundreds of GPUs within a rack on high-bandwidth low-latency AI fabrics. The rack is the new unit of compute. Customers are deploying rack-scale architectures because models have outgrown single-server limits; connecting vast numbers of GPUs requires thinking and operating at rack scale.

While others emphasize proprietary closed ecosystems, we anchor an open rack-scale architecture around support for open standards, intelligent software, multi-protocol coverage, and a purpose-built portfolio. At the foundation we have Aries Smart PCIe retimers—central to the 1.0 rollout and to fixing signal integrity as accelerators and complex connectors multiply in a rack. We have Taurus Smart DSP retimers scaling Ethernet from 100 to 800 gig for scale-out. We have LEO CXL smart memory controllers for memory expansion and pooling so GPUs use memory more efficiently. And we have Scorpio AI fabric switches—intelligent fabric platforms orchestrating traffic between multi-accelerator systems.

End customers want multi-vendor flexibility and an open ecosystem so they can choose XPUs, CPUs, supply-chain partners, and deployment models without lock-in.

On products: Aries and Taurus PCIe retimers have shipped for about six years; PCIe Gen 4 and Gen 5 are in production across hyperscalers. We were early to PCIe Gen 6 retimers now in high-volume production at multiple hyperscalers while competitors remain in early evaluation. Ethernet retimers span 100 to 800 gig for scale-out, also in cable-module form factors with partners for active electrical cables. This year we announced the Aries PCIe Smart Gearbox to bridge rate mismatch between cutting-edge PCIe Gen 6 and established Gen 5 ecosystems without losing throughput—for example better use of lanes from Gen 6 XPUs into x16 links at different data rates. It comes in smaller eight-lane to sixteen-lane and larger dual eight-lane to dual sixteen-lane form factors.

Scorpio AI fabric switches are built for AI workloads: P-Series for mixed head-node traffic among GPU, switch, SSD, and NIC; X-Series for higher lane counts and the scale-up backend bottleneck.

Chris Blackburn continues with how these products show up in customer deployments. At booth B33 we show an “open rack” reference versus proprietary rack-scale designs—how Astera and partner products combine toward an open rack standard, recognizing end customers will still customize. The display includes a reference XPU tray (XPUs, CPU, memory, scale-out NICs, switches, storage) and a scale-up switch platform based on Scorpio X connecting XPUs inside the rack. Multiple protocols—scale-up, scale-out, PCIe, CXL—require a healthy ecosystem and collaboration.

On the XPU platform, Aries PCIe and CXL retimers and Taurus Ethernet smart retimers sit ahead of backplane connectors; larger packages represent XPUs. Accelerator boards often cable to a PCIe switch board where Scorpio P-Series ties SSDs, scale-out NIC, CPU, and GPU. On the compute and memory complex, DCMHS connects CXL memory through LEO and Aries gearbox where—for example—a x8 Gen 6 path must translate to x16 Gen 5. The scale-up switch is Scorpio X with the same retimer placement before the backplane. This is a representative starting point for how platforms converge.

Servers are increasingly modular. We highlight modules integrating Aries retimers or Scorpio switches with card-edge, mezzanine, backplane, or near-chip options so retimers are easy to add and architects can choose active retiming or passive links where appropriate.

We have six demos at the OCP show: the open rack, an active cable backplane, a PCIe Gen 6 fabric with industry SSDs and GPUs and switches at Gen 6, 200 gig per lane Ethernet cabling, a CXL memory chatbot for inference, and rack management and OpenBMC demos. Chris mentions a follow-on talk at 3:30 on the active cable backplane and additional security sessions. We welcome questions at the side of the stage—thank you for your time.
